<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 3:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I260dc1c0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>3.</label.designator><headtext>Statutory Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f2ce4682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>3:13.</label.designator><headtext>Informant privilege</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The identity of a government informant is privileged information in Georgia.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic265c7c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] The law recognizes different types of government informers. <eos/><bos/>For example, some act as tipsters (informer-witnesses) while others serve as decoys (informer-participants).<eos/><bos/> Although this issue was previously unsettled,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic265c7c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] it is now clear that the identity of both types of informants fall within the scope of the privilege.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic265c7c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] When determining whether the identity of an informant may be disclosed, the issue is not the informant&apos;s level of involvement in the criminal activity, but whether the disclosure <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“is material to the defense on the issue of guilt or punishment”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> of the defendant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic265eed07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] The informant privilege belongs to the State. <eos/><bos/>Neither the informant nor the police officer who used the informant may claim it, though a witness will often claim it on the State&apos;s behalf when asked to identify the informer. <eos/><bos/>A police officer, however, may not claim the privilege at a hearing before his superior officers in the police department.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic265eed17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The type of proceeding affects how a trial court determines whether an informant&apos;s identity should be protected by privilege. <eos/><bos/>For instance, an informant&apos;s identity is privileged on a motion to suppress because the only issue is probable cause rather than the <page no="75"/>guilt or innocence of the defendant.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic265eed27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] Other proceedings require the trial court to conduct a two-step hearing into the matter, including an in camera review of the informant&apos;s identity and testimony.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic26615e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1977113426" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie93001a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Thornton v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic26615e17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court addressed this issue in light of a motion made pursuant to <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1963125353" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie930c4f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brady v. Maryland</ital></cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2663cf07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>] The Court held that the trial court is required to conduct a hearing on the merits of the <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1963125353" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie93272a27fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brady</ital></cite.query> motion, and, if it finds the evidence material under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1963125353" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie93272a67fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brady</ital></cite.query>, the court must weigh it against the state&apos;s privilege to protect the identity of the informant under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1957120342" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie93272aa7fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Roviaro v. U.S.</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic2663cf17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] The Court stated, <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“In most instances, where the information is material under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1963125353" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie93420527fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brady</ital></cite.query>, it will also be required under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1957120342" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie93420567fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Roviaro</ital></cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>But this may not always be so and to do otherwise is to abrogate entirely the state&apos;s privilege whenever a <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1963125353" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie934205a7fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Brady</ital></cite.query> issue is successfully raised by the defendant.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic26664007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>] In that case, the court must look at the particular circumstances of each case and take into consideration the crime charged, the possible defenses, the possible significance of the informer&apos;s testimony, and other relevant factors.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic26664017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>It has been widely recognized that former <begin.quote ID="QT_0007"/>“<cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-21" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie93531c07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 24-9-21(4)</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-27" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie93531c17fbf11ea988285db8533e975">24-9-27(d)</cite.query> [current <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie93531c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 24-5-501(a)(4)</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-505" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie93531c37fbf11ea988285db8533e975">24-5-505</cite.query>] prohibit disclosure of the identity of a confidential informant who was not an eyewitness to the offense being prosecuted.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0007"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic26664027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13<page no="76"/></footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic265c7c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1945103646" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92999027fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Anderson v. State, 72 Ga. App. 487, 34 S.E.2d 110 (1945)</cite.query> (recognizing the privilege protecting the identity of an informant).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic265c7c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1954105030" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92a35427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Crosby v. State, 90 Ga. App. 63, 82 S.E.2d 38 (1954)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1975132504" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92a35457fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Taylor v. State, 136 Ga. App. 31, 220 S.E.2d 49 (1975)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic265c7c27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1977113426" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92aaa727fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Thornton v. State, 238 Ga. 160, 231 S.E.2d 729 (1977)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1957120342" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie92aaa757fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Roviaro v. U.S., 353 U.S. 53, 77 S. Ct. 623, 1 L. Ed. 2d 639 (1957)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="2030435106" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92aaa797fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Reid v. State, 321 Ga. App. 653, 742 S.E.2d 166 (2013)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic265eed07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1977113426" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92bbbe27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Thornton v. State, 238 Ga. 160, 165, 231 S.E.2d 729 (1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1976135540" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92bbbe57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Connally v. State, 237 Ga. 203, 227 S.E.2d 352 (1976)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment vacated on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1977118705" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie92bbbe87fbf11ea988285db8533e975">429 U.S. 245, 97 S. Ct. 546, 50 L. Ed. 2d 444 (1977)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic265eed17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1968132546" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92ca6427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Williams v. Mayor and Bd. of Aldermen of City of Atlanta, 118 Ga. App. 271, 163 S.E.2d 239 (1968)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="75"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic265eed27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1977113425" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92d42827fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Keith v. State, 238 Ga. 157, 231 S.E.2d 727 (1977)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic26615e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In such cases, the court will initially hear evidence to determine (1) whether <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“the confidential informant is an alleged informer-witness or informer-participant whose testimony appears to be material to the defense on the issue of guilt or punishment,”<end.quote refid="QT_0003"/> (2) whether <begin.quote ID="QT_0006"/>“the testimony for the prosecution and the defense is or will be in conflict,”<end.quote refid="QT_0006"/> and (3) whether <begin.quote ID="QT_0005"/>“the confidential informant is the only available witness who could amplify or contradict the testimony of these witnesses.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0005"/> If all of these questions are answered in the affirmative, the trial court must then conduct an in camera hearing of the informant&apos;s testimony and <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“balance the public interest in protecting the flow of information against the defendant&apos;s right to prepare for his defense.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0004"/> <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1998038325" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92f17427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Grant v. State, 230 Ga. App. 330, 331, 496 S.E.2d 325 (1998)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1998082286" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92f65627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Harvey v. State, 232 Ga. App. 21, 500 S.E.2d 916 (1998)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="2001112306" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie92f65657fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Turner v. State, 247 Ga. App. 775, 544 S.E.2d 765 (2001)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic26615e17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1977113426" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie9304fc27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Thornton v. State, 238 Ga. 160, 231 S.E.2d 729 (1977)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2663cf07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1963125353" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie93113127fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83, 83 S. Ct. 1194, 10 L. Ed. 2d 215 (1963)</cite.query> (holding that the prosecution&apos;s suppression of evidence favorable to the accused upon request (by whom?) violates due process where the evidence is material to either guilt or punishment).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2663cf17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1957120342" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie932c0c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Roviaro v. U.S., 353 U.S. 53, 77 S. Ct. 623, 1 L. Ed. 2d 639 (1957)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic26664007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="1977113426" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie9346e727fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Thornton v. State, 238 Ga. 160, 164, 231 S.E.2d 729 (1977)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic26664017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="2038876360" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie934bc927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">McGhee v. State, 337 Ga. App. 150, 786 S.E.2d 527 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic26664027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13<page no="76"/></label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="2001112306" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie935a6f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Turner v. State, 247 Ga. App. 775, 544 S.E.2d 765 (2001)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="2009398385" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie935a6f57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Little v. State, 280 Ga. App. 60, 61, 633 S.E.2d 403 (2006)</cite.query> (citing <cite.query w-src-number="0287018110" w-serial-number="2001112306" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie935a6f87fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Turner</ital></cite.query>).<eos/><page no="76"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 3:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
